    "summary": "TOCTOU between the comparison-dependents pre-check and the DELETE commit: a concurrently created comparison check makes session.commit() raise an uncaught IntegrityError from the RESTRICT FK, producing exactly the raw 500 the ConnectionInUseError comment claims to prevent.",
    "failure_scenario": "Request A: POST /suites/{sid}/checks creating a comparison check with source_connection_id=X commits just after Request B's dependents SELECT (which saw zero rows) but before B's session.commit() in delete_connection. B's DELETE FROM connections violates fk_checks_source_connection_id_connections; the IntegrityError is not caught in delete_connection and no global IntegrityError handler exists (core/errors.py registers only DataQError/HTTP/validation/Exception handlers), so the client gets a generic 500 instead of the designed 409, with the failed transaction left for the get_db teardown to roll back."
  },
  {
    "file": "backend/app/services/check_service.py",
    "line": 313,
    "summary": "config.max_rows validation accepts JSON booleans: isinstance(True, int) is True in Python, so {\"max_rows\": true} passes the 'positive integer' gate and persists.",
    "failure_scenario": "POST /suites/{sid}/checks with a comparison config containing \"max_rows\": true (an easy JSON slip for 'enabled') returns 201 instead of the intended 422 ('config.max_rows must be a positive integer when set'). The check persists with max_rows=True; when the #794 runner lands and uses it as a row cap, True == 1 silently caps the diff to a single row, making the comparison pass/fail on 1 row while the author believes the whole dataset is reconciled."
