    "failure_scenario": "POST /suites/{sid}/checks with kind='comparison' and config {\"source\": {\"table\": \"T\"}, \"keys\": [\"<10 MB string>\"], \"garbage\": \"<10 MB string>\"} is accepted (the keys loop only requires a non-empty str; extra keys are never inspected), whereas the same payload on an expectation check is 422'd by _validate_config_strings. The multi-megabyte config is then re-emitted on every GET /checks, every version snapshot (record_check_version copies config), and every suite export — bloating check_versions rows and API responses with no cap, unlike every other check kind."
  },
  {
    "file": "backend/app/services/connection_service.py",
    "line": 389,
    "summary": "The delete-guard 409 detail is silently truncated to 10 dependents with no total count or truncation marker, while the message ('repoint or delete them first') implies the list is complete.",
    "failure_scenario": "A connection is the comparison source of 25 checks. DELETE /connections/{id} returns 409 listing exactly 10 checks; the user repoints/deletes those 10, retries, and gets another 409 listing 10 different checks, repeatedly — nothing in the payload (no 'total', no 'truncated' flag) tells them 15 more existed, so a scripted remediation that trusts detail.checks as exhaustive loops or fails."
  },
  {
    "file": "backend/app/mcp/server.py",
    "line": 347,
    "summary": "The MCP create_check tool accepts arbitrary kind (now including the authorable 'comparison') but has no source_connection_id parameter, so every MCP comparison-authoring attempt dead-ends on an error whose remedy the tool cannot express.",
    "failure_scenario": "An AI client calls the create_check MCP tool with kind='comparison' (valid per _V1_SUPPORTED_KINDS, so validate_kind passes); check_service.create_check is invoked with source_connection_id defaulting to None and raises 'a comparison check needs source_connection_id — ...'. The client follows the actionable message but the tool schema has no such field to supply, so comparison checks are un-authorable via /mcp with a misleading retry-inviting error rather than an upfront unsupported-kind message."
  }
]
```

Verified non-issues a reviewer might have flagged (checked, all clean): the migration's `op.f()` names exactly match the metadata naming convention outputs (`ck_%(table_name)s_%(constraint_name)s` → `ck_checks_comparison_source_presence`, no double-prefixing since `op.f` bypasses convention expansion); downgrade drops the same literal names in correct order; the model CheckConstraint expression is byte-identical to the migration's; `update_check` correctly uses the existing `check.source_connection_id` when a PATCH omits it and re-validates effective values before mutating; all `export_suite` callers were updated to the new `(session, suite)` signature (only `api/v1/suites.py`; no test/script callers); suite deletion still works (ORM delete-orphan removes check rows before the suite, so the RESTRICT FK on `checks.source_connection_id` never fires); alembic chain has a single head `b7c8d9e0f1a2`; and `probe.py`/import/seed paths construct only `kind='expectation'` rows that satisfy the new CHECK constraint.

